node.text: Rio De Janeiro, Brazil: Witness the inspiring story of Tuany, a 23-year-old ballet dancer who started a dance company for young girls in the middle of one of Rio De Janeiro’s most dangerous favelas. She gives students hope for a better future and a safe space away from the violent world around them.

node.text: Grand Caillou/Dulac, Louisiana, U.S.A.: Meet Chief Shirell, the first female chief of her southern Louisiana tribe. Her ancestors have lived on the land for hundreds of years, and they are now expected to be among the United States’ first climate refugees. Chief Shirell can’t stop the storms, but she is impacting the legacy of her ancestors, the lives of her community today and the future of her people.

node.text: Memphis, Tennessee, U.S.A.: Meet Kayla, who has dedicated her life to helping homeless transgender women of color in Memphis, Tennessee. She is building more than two dozen houses across Memphis for transgender women who need safety and a place to call home.

node.text: With many of Africa’s key species, including elephants, heading toward extinction, @int.anti.poaching.foundation Akashinga is a radical, new and highly effective weapon against poaching. Founded in Zimbabwe by former Australian special forces soldier and anti-poaching leader Damien Mander (@damien_mander), the women-only team of rangers is revolutionizing the way animals are protected, communities are empowered — and its members’ own lives are being transformed. Mander’s innovative approach to conservation calls for community buy-in rather than full-on armed assault against poachers: If a community understands the economic benefits of preserving animals, then it will eliminate poaching without an armed struggle. Executive produced by three-time Academy Award winner James Cameron (@jamescameronofficial) and directed by Maria Wilhelm, AKASHINGA: THE BRAVE ONES is a celebration of the courage, conservation and unorthodox thinking that’s leading to massive positive change.

node.text: Photo by @stevewinterphoto /Blood is taken from three lions in South Africa that are being moved to Malawi to repopulate lions there. I was able to be on the ground with the conservation group African Parks to document the immobilization of the first round of lions from South Africa to Liwonde National Park in Malawi. This is all part of a predator restoration project where @AfricanParksNetwork has reintroduced lions and cheetahs to Liwonde, helping to restore the park ecologically as well as to boost tourism, creating much-needed revenue for local communities. It’s a hopeful story, not just for lions but for all wildlife and people living in these areas. Peter Fearnhead, CEO of African Parks, said: “Very simply, if a park is not being managed, then it will be lost. We have two options, one is we allow these places to disappear. The other is we make our own plan.” By working with governments and local communities, they're moving to restore protected areas across Africa. Follow @africanparksnetwork to learn more about their work across Africa.  @lionrecovery

node.text: Photo by @paulnicklen / So much of wildlife photography is perseverance. On this particular assignment for @NatGeo, we spent 90 days searching British Columbia's rugged shoreline for signs of coastal wolves—an elusive community that feeds almost exclusively from the ocean. On eighty of those, we huddled in blinds as their tantalizing howls carried over the water; on eight, we caught fleeting glimpses of them in the distance; and on just four, we got close enough to capture images. Sometimes a single photo requires an investment of hundreds of hours of trekking, tracking, and trying again and again to get it right, but the effort is always worth it. Follow me @PaulNicklen to see more images of sea wolves captured during my countless hours in the wild. #Wolf #SeaWolf #CoastalWolf #BC #BritishColumbia #Canada #Wildlife #Photography #Perseverance

node.text: Photo by Robbie Shone @shonephoto / Very little remains of the Sulzenauferner (glacier) in Austria. In the night, it's an eerie, somber, and peaceful place. The only thing that disturbs the peace is the sound of occasional blocks of ice tumbling down the mountainside, releasing an almighty crash into the landscape below. They sound like thunder. The noise echoes around the walls of the valley and breaks the deadly silence. The jagged towers of the icefall rise high above the lake, pointing toward the snow-covered summit of the Zuckerhütl, the highest mountain in the Stubai Alps. In the warmer months, pieces of ice rain down from the glacier more frequently. It’s simply disappearing before our very eyes.

node.text: Photos by Keith Ladzinski @ladzinski / Found in Central, East and southern Africa, lilac-breasted rollers always make for a great sighting. These colorful birds prefer open savanna, where they can hunt insects and small reptiles. Generally perching on high branches to survey the land, these territorial birds are often seen aggressively chasing away the competition. I photographed these two in the Timbavati of South Africa. node.text: Tagging along with rangers, David Chancellor @chancellordavid captured a collared elephant being moved across the Mara River and away from farmers’ fields in Kenya. An elephant can destroy a farmer’s entire crop in one night. Rangers from @maraelephantproject protect farmers’ crops, often armed with little more than firecrackers and torches. By collaring persistent offenders and developing close relationships with the community, the rangers mitigate conflict before it occurs, protecting both the elephants and farmers. The helicopter is an invaluable tool, though they also experiment with less expensive methods of mitigation, such as bee hive "fences," drones (which sound like bees to the elephants), and chili balls.

node.text: Photo by Pete McBride @pedromcbride / When I started out as a photographer, I lived here, in this one-stove, canvas-covered lodgepole teepee at 12,200 feet (3,700m) in the Gore Range of the Colorado Rockies. It was often cold, but life was simple and dictated by light and weather. I frequently practiced doing long exposures with slide film, which required six-hour exposures to get enough light—as seen in this image. For more from the American West, follow @pedromcbride. #starlight #nightsky #nature #petemcbride

node.text: Photo by @mattiasklumofficial / Morning in the Danum Valley, Malaysian Borneo. This rainforest is estimated to be at least 130 million years old, making it one of the oldest rainforests in the world (and twice as old as the Amazon rainforest). Rich in biodiversity, Borneo provides habitat for about 15,000 known species of flowering plants, more than 3,000 tree species, 221 terrestrial mammal species, and 420 bird species. After years of work in Borneo, I can say it's one of the places in the world that's deeply engrained in my heart! Visit @mattiasklumofficial to follow our work. #borneo #biodiversity #science #conservation #rainforest #protectethnicminorities #creativity @thephotosociety

node.text: Photo by Cristina Mittermeier @Mitty / The soft pink hues of sunset tinted the water as I waded slowly through the briny shallows of the Ria Lagartos, a shallow estuary that graces the northern shores of the Yucatan Peninsula. The name literally translates to “alligator river” but it's neither a river nor does it have alligators. Instead, it’s a vast wetland that serves as a critical migratory stopover for birds, including spectacular flocks of flamingos. The birds congregate in the estuaries that feed the Gulf of Mexico, where the dense concentration of salt in the water attracts their preferred prey, brine shrimp. It's just one of the many natural wonders you can find in Mexico, the country where I was born and where I first discovered my passion for ocean life. Follow me @Mitty to hear more about my experiences in the field with @NatGeo and my team @SeaLegacy.
